        "questionText":  "The figure shows all subnets used in a small lab network. An engineer configures the command ip route 10.4.64.0 255.255.254.0 10.4.12.2 command on router R1, and the router adds the command to its running-config file. However, a static route does not appear in router R1\u0026rsquo;s routing table. Which answers give a reason why R1 would not add the static route to the table?",
        "explanation":  "For the correct answer, only a few reasons exist that result in the router accepting the command into the configuration while also not adding a route to the routing table. To accept the command into the configuration, it must have correct syntax. Also, the two numeric parameters must pass a test in which the first number is a subnet ID when using the configured mask, rather than being an address or a subnet broadcast address. IOS would reject the command if the first numeric value was not a subnet ID.\n\nOnce in the configuration, IOS would not add the route to the routing table if:\n\n\n\tA better route (with a lower administrative distance) already exists in the routing table\n\tThe static route\u0026rsquo;s next-hop address (if configured) is not reachable by the router.\n\tThe static route\u0026rsquo;s outgoing interface (if configured) is not in an up/up state.\n\n\nOnly one of those reasons appears in the answers and is the correct answer in this case. R1 would not have a connected route matching next-hop address 10.4.12.2 if the link between the routers were down, for instance.\n\nFor the incorrect answer that mentions the lack of an administrative distance parameter, that parameter is optional, defaulting to 1, and the command is fine without that parameter.\n\nFor the answer claiming that the first numeric parameter is not a subnet ID, it is incorrect. You can do the math on the values in the ip route command to confirm that fact. However, the question tells you the router accepted the command and added it to the configuration, which confirms that the router thinks the values are acceptable.\n\nFinally, one answer claims that the subnet listed by the command is not the subnet connected to router R2. That claim is not true; it is the subnet listed off R2 in the figure. However, even if the ip route command referred to a non-existent subnet, it would still add the route to the routing table. Router R1 has no way of knowing if the subnet exists or not.",
