        "explanation":  "The question requires that the command not be changed by IOS when added to the router configuration. In some cases, IOS will change the subnet value (the first value) in the OSPF network command when you add it to the configuration. By convention, the first numeric value must be the numerically lowest number in the range defined by the combined subnet plus wildcard fields. If not, IOS changes your value to the lowest number in the range. \n\nFor instance, in this case, the network 172.16.30.1 0.0.0.255 area 0 command defines a range with the idea of \u0026quot;all addresses that begin 172.16.30\u0026quot;. Numerically, the range is 172.16.30.0 \u0026ndash; 172.16.30.255. However, with an initial value of 172.16.30.1, which is not the number at the low end of the range, IOS would change the command to network 172.16.30.0 0.0.0.255 area 0.\n\nTwo incorrect answers have values in the subnet field that would result in IOS changing the command, making them incorrect based on the wording of this question:\n\nnetwork 172.16.30.1 0.0.0.255\u0026hellip; becomes network 172.16.30.0 0.0.0.255\u0026hellip;\n\nnetwork 172.16.30.1 0.0.1.255\u0026hellip; becomes network 172.16.30.0 0.0.1.255\u0026hellip;\n\nFor the two remaining answers, one creates an address range that includes all three interfaces, and one matches only two interfaces, not matching interface G0/0/0\u0026#39;s IP address. You can easily find the range of values matched by the network command. Once in the configuration file, the command has the number at the low end of the range as the first value. You simply add the two values (subnet and wildcard mask) to find the high end of the range. In this case:\n\nnetwork 172.16.30.0 0.0.0.255\u0026hellip; has a range of: 172.16.30.0 \u0026ndash; 172.16.30.255\n\nnetwork 172.16.30.0 0.0.1.255\u0026hellip; has a range of: 172.16.30.0 \u0026ndash; 172.16.31.255\n\nBased on comparing those ranges to the interface addresses, only the network 172.16.30.0 0.0.1.255\u0026hellip; command matches all three interfaces.",
