        "explanation":  "A few different commands are typically used to configure basic NTP; they include the ntp server, ntp peer, and the ntp master commands. Specifically:\n\n\tThe\u0026nbsp;ntp server\u0026nbsp;command defines the IP address of some other NTP server, so that the local device synchronizes its time based on that NTP server\u0026#39;s time. Also, a device configured with the ntp server\u0026nbsp;command can act as an NTP server for other devices as well, as long as the device also has some other primary clock source (for instance, as configured with the ntp master command).\u0026nbsp;\n\n\tThe ntp peer command indicates that a device intends to both synchronize its time with the configured peer, and to supply time information back to that peer.\n\n\tThe ntp master command configures a device as an authoritative clock source. This command is usually used along with the ntp server command on core devices to ensure that if the core device loses its primary clock source (as configured with the ntp server command), it can still offer an authoritative clock source to other devices that use it as their primary clock source.\n\n\tIn this scenario, R2 would need to use the ntp server 10.10.10.1 command to use R1 as its primary clock source.",
