        "explanation":  "The first octet value of 125 is within the range from 1-126 inclusive, which tells us that the address is in a class A network. Class A networks use a default mask of 255.0.0.0 (or /8).\n\n\tThe question shows mask 255.255.128.0, which when converted to prefix notation is /17. The number of binary 1\u0026#39;s in the mask (17) defines the combined number of network and subnet bits, so: 8 network bits plus 9 subnet bits equals the 17 combined bits per the mask, supplying the correct answer of 9 subnet bits.\n\n\tOf the incorrect answers, all imply a different mask than the one shown in the question stem:\n\n\t\n\t\t10 bits: The mask in a class A network (8 network bits), with 10 subnet bits, defines a /18 mask, which in dotted decimal is 255.255.192.0 - a different mask than the one in the question.\n\t\n\t\t11 bits: The mask in a class A network (8 network bits), with 11 subnet bits, defines a /19 mask, which in dotted decimal is 255.255.224.0 - a different mask than the one in the question.\n\t\n\t\t12 bits: The mask in a class A network (8 network bits), with 12 subnet bits, defines a /20 mask, which in dotted decimal is 255.255.240.0 - a different mask than the one in the question.\n\n\n\t\u0026nbsp;",
