        "questionText":  "The figure identifies addresses, subnets, and subnet masks used in a small internetwork. The routers have been configured with those IP addresses along with a routing protocol. All PCs can successfully ping each other, and all routers have been configured with the ip subnet-zero command. Which answers accurately describe the zero and broadcast subnets traversed in various pings between the PCs?",
        "explanation":  "In any subnetted network, the numerically lowest subnet ID is the zero subnet of that network. The name comes from the fact that in binary, the subnet bits have an all 0s value. In decimal, the zero subnet number always matches the classful network number. The zero subnets in the figure are:\n\n\n\tThe R4 LAN (172.30.0.0/21)\n\tThe R3 LAN\u0026nbsp;(10.0.0.0/14)\n\tThe R1-R2 WAN link (192.168.5.0/30)\n\n\nIn any subnetted network, the highest subnet ID is the broadcast subnet. The name comes from the coincidence that, in a\u0026nbsp;broadcast subnet, the subnet\u0026#39;s\u0026nbsp;subnet broadcast address is the same number as the network-wide broadcast address. Regardless, the broadcast subnets in the figure are:\n\n\n\tThe R1-R4\u0026nbsp;WAN link (192.168.7.128/25)\n\n\nFor instance, the subnet number on the R1-R4 link is 192.168.7.128, with a range of valid addresses 192.168.7.129 to .254, with 192.168.7.255 as the subnet broadcast address. The network-wide broadcast has 255 in the last octet of Class C\u0026mdash;in other words, 192.168.7.255. Therefore, the R1-R4 link is a broadcast subnet. It is the only broadcast subnet in the figure.\n\nFinally, note that the\u0026nbsp;R1-R3 WAN link does not use subnetting because it uses class C addresses with the default class C mask of /24.\n\nPredict the path messages take between any pair of PCs to find the correct answers. Then you can look at the above analysis to see if those packets traversed any zero or broadcast subnets.\n\n\u0026nbsp;",
