        "questionText":  "Which of the following Quality of Service (QoS) scheduling mechanisms are considered advanced queuing techniques on Cisco routers? (Select all that apply.)",
        "explanation":  "QoS (Quality of Service) scheduling mechanisms manage how packets are queued and transmitted to prioritize traffic.\n\nAdvanced queuing techniques on Cisco routers include:\n\n- **Class-Based Weighted Fair Queuing (CBWFQ):** Allows classifying traffic into classes and assigning guaranteed bandwidth to each, with sharing of unused bandwidth.\n- **Low Latency Queueing (LLQ):** Builds on CBWFQ by adding a strict priority queue for delay-sensitive traffic (e.g., VoIP), ensuring it\u0027s served first (with policing to prevent starvation).\n- **Weighted Fair Queuing (WFQ):** Dynamically provides proportional bandwidth to all active flows based on their weight, preventing any single flow from dominating.\n\n- **Priority Queueing (PQ)** is a simpler, older mechanism that always serves the highest priority queue first. While it prioritizes, it can lead to starvation of lower-priority traffic and is not considered as advanced or flexible as the fair queuing methods.",
