        "explanation":  "In this example, PC1 and PC4 reside in different subnets, with one router between them. As a result, the router de-encapsulates the IP packet (holding the ICMP message) from the Ethernet frame, discarding the old Ethernet header and trailer - and then adding a new Ethernet header and trailer. Each frame uses a destination MAC address of a device on the same LAN or broadcast domain.\u0026nbsp;\n\nConsidering an ICMP Echo message sent by PC1 to PC4, the frame encapsulating the ICMP Request message uses:\n\n\n\n\tThe IP header shows PC1\u0026#39;s IPv4 address as the source and PC4\u0026#39;s IPv4 address as the destination.\n\tThe Ethernet header of the frame, as sent by PC1, includes a source MAC of \u0026nbsp;PC1\u0026#39;s MAC and a destination MAC of R1-Gi0/0\u0026#39;s MAC.\n\tThe Ethernet header of the frame after the router routes the packet (including de-encapsulation and re-encapsulation) shows\u0026nbsp;a source MAC of R1-Gi0/1\u0026#39;s MAC and PC4\u0026#39;s MAC\u0026nbsp;address as the destination. \u0026nbsp;\n\n\n\nIn the reverse direction, with PC4 sending an ICMP Echo Reply:\n\n\n\tThe IP header shows PC4\u0026#39;s IPv4 address as the source and PC1\u0026#39;s IPv4 address as the destination.\n\tThe Ethernet header of the frame sent by PC4 shows PC4\u0026#39;s MAC address as the source and R1-Gi0/1\u0026#39;s MAC as the destination.\n\tThe Ethernet header of the frame after the router routes the packet (including de-encapsulation and re-encapsulation) shows the\u0026nbsp;R1-Gi0/0\u0026#39;s MAC as the source and PC1\u0026#39;s MAC address as the destination.\n\n\nIf you apply all these facts to the various answers, you can rule in and rule out each correct and incorrect answer, respectively.",
