        "questionText":  "All PCs and switch ports in the figure use IEEE autonegotiation. What would be the resulting speed and duplex of the link between the switch and Host B?",
        "explanation":  "For proper communication, both interfaces must operate at the same speed. In this case, the host has a maximum speed of 100 Mbps, and the switch has a maximum of 1000 Mbps (1 Gbps), so they will autonegotiate to use 100 Mbps. Autonegotiation will also use the best duplex option (Full).",
        "difficulty":  "2",
        "comments":  "\u003cp\u003e10/13 - ok as-is \u0026quot;On this one, you paraphrased what you believe the book to claim, and I think that\u0026rsquo;s the problem. You paraphrased some rules from the book but omitted the context. That text in the book describes what happens when one device disables auto negotiation. It goes on to say how Cisco switches work in that case. However, this question clearly states that the PCs and switch port use auto negotiation, so the rules you quoted do not apply here. Instead, the endpoints on each link choose the fastest speed that both support and the best duplex that both support, full being better than half.\u0026quot;\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e10/4 - query to Au\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e8/8 - ok as-is \u0026quot;Interesting, it looks like you are referring to the logic used when IEEE auto-negotiation does not work. In this question, it is working, as detailed in the explanation to the question. In short, both ends state their best speed and best duplex, and they agree to use the fastest speed that both support at use the better duplex (full) if both support it. In this case, one supports 1 Gbps, the other support 100 Mbps, and both support full duplex. So, they agree to the fastest speed that they both support (100 Mbps), and to use the best duplex they both support (full). There\u0026rsquo;s no need to use auto-negotiation defaults for duplex because the auto-negotiation process is working, with both devices stating their abilities.\u0026quot;\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e8/4, 7/26 - query to Au\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e6/28 - ok as-is, \u0026quot; With both the switch and PC using auto negotiation, they communicate the idea that they each can support both half and full duplex, and then they both choose the better option: full duplex. I wonder if you\u0026rsquo;re thinking of the default choice of auto negotiation that would happen if one device did not use auto negotiation. For example, if PC B disabled auto negotiation, SW1 could sense that PC B was using 100 Mbps - without using autonegotation but by sensing the electrical signal - and choose the correct 100 Mbps speed. But without those auto negotiation messages, that\u0026rsquo;s the case in which SW1 would have to use the default duplex, which as you noted would be half duplex if the speed is 10 or 100 Mbps. Different case in this question - both ends use autonegotiation, so they both choose the better duplex setting.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e6/23 - query to Au\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e6/17 - sent reader suggestion to au,\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e8/18 - ok as-is, Cisco does not use a separate auto negotiation standard. I wonder if you might have misread the question. The question stem states that auto negotiation is enabled. IEEE auto negotiation chooses the best (that is, full) duplex supported by both endpoints when auto negotiation is enabled and working. I wonder if you are thinking of the IEEE auto negotiation choice when the device on the other end of the link does not use auto negotiation, in which case at 10 and 100 MBps, the duplex would default to half. The book gets into comparing both sets of conditions (Vol 1 Chapter 7.)\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e7/28 - query to Au, 11/18 - ok as-is, 10/29 - query to Au\u003c/p\u003e\n",
