        "questionId":  "075C16C2-124F-48A0-AC3C-362E1E1088EE",
        "questionText":  "In the figure, in VLAN 1, all switches have mostly default STP settings, and all trunks are up. The only nondefault setting is that the port cost of SW2\u0026rsquo;s fa0/1 interface has been changed to 1. Which statements are true regarding the behavior of STP in this network, for VLAN 1, when the STP topology has stabilized? (Refer to the exhibit for information related to the figure.)",
        "explanation":  "The root election is still based on the lowest bridge ID. With default priority values, the switch that has the lowest MAC address\u0026mdash;SW1\u0026mdash;wins. SW2\u0026rsquo;s fa0/1, SW3\u0026rsquo;s fa0/1, and SW4\u0026rsquo;s fa0/1 all receive a zero-cost BPDU from SW1, and each of these ports becomes the root port on its respective switches.\n\n\t\u0026nbsp;\n\n\tWhen SW2 receives the zero-cost Hello from SW1 (root), it forwards the Hellos, after adding SW2\u0026rsquo;s fa0/1 interface STP port cost to the original received cost. SW2\u0026rsquo;s forwarded Hellos will have a cost of 1. SW3 will forward a Hello onto the trunk between itself and SW2, out SW3\u0026rsquo;s fa0/2 interface, based on SW3\u0026rsquo;s default fa0/1 port cost of 19. SW2 is advertising the lowest-cost Hello onto the trunk between itself and SW3, so SW2\u0026rsquo;s fa0/3 becomes the designated port on that segment.",
