        "questionText":  "Refer to the exhibit; switch SW3 is receiving only two hello BPDUs, both of which identify the same root switch, received on the two interfaces listed. SW3 has no STP-related configuration commands. The hello received on Fa0/13 lists root cost 10, and the hello received on Gi0/1 lists root cost 20. Which of the following is true about STP on SW3?",
        "explanation":  "For a switch to determine its own root cost, the switch adds its received root cost (as advertised by neighbors) to the local switch\u0026#39;s interfaces. In this case, while the advertised cost is lower for the Hello SW3 receives on its Fa0/13 interface (cost 10), SW3 must then add the cost of F0/13. So SW3\u0026#39;s root cost out its F0/13 would be 29 (10 + 19). While the cost SW3 receives in the Hello coming in the GigabitEthernet link is 20, when SW3 adds the G0/1 cost to the link, SW3\u0026#39;s root cost out its G0/1 would be 24 (20 + 4). Because of this, SW3 will choose its Gi0/1 link as its root port.\n\n\tRegarding G0/1 becoming the designated port, it will not, because G0/1 is the root port.\n\n\tRegarding whether SW3\u0026rsquo;s Fa0/13 will become a designated port, we know that SW3 is receiving a Hello on F0/13 with root cost 10. SW3 would advertise it\u0026#39;s root cost as 24. The designated port is the port out which the least-cost Hello is advertised, so the other switch off SW3\u0026#39;s F0/13 port would win the election, and SW3\u0026#39;s F0/13 would not be the designated port.",
