        "explanation":  "\u0026nbsp;\n\n\tTCP connections begin with a TCP handshake of three messages, in this order:\n\n\t\n\t\ta TCP SYN (from the client to the server)\n\t\n\t\ta TCP SYN+ACK (from the server back to the client)\n\t\n\t\ta TCP ACK (from the client back to the server)\n\n\n\tIn this case, PC1 as the client initiating the TCP connection sends the TCP SYN, and PC2 replies by sending the TCP SYN+ACK.\n\t\n\tFor the port numbers, all TCP messages sent by a host put that host\u0026#39;s port number into the source port field of the TCP header. In this case, because PC2 sends the message, the source port will be the port PC2 is using, which is port 80. As a result, the correct answer lists PC2 as the sending host, with source port 80.",
