        "questionText":  "An engineer wants to troubleshoot an issue between PC1 and PC2 but has no access to either PC. So, the engineer issues a ping 192.168.3.100 command from R1, and the ping was successful. Are there any routes needed between PC1 and PC2 that would not be verified as working by that successful ping from R1?",
        "explanation":  "This question highlights some common mistakes regarding what a ping command does and does not test.\u0026nbsp;\u0026nbsp;A ping from R1 to PC2 verifies the connectivity between R1\u0026#39;s Gi0/2 interface and the rest of the network to its right. However, that command leaves out a few items:\n\n\n\tTesting between PC1 and R1\u0026#39;s G0/1 interface, including PC1\u0026#39;s default router setting.\n\tTesting R2\u0026#39;s route to the subnet where PC1 resides.\n\n\nA better test from R1 can force a test of R2\u0026#39;s route to PC1\u0026#39;s subnet by using an extended ping command and a source IP address from R1\u0026#39;s Gi0/1 interface. On the return packet, router R2 will need to forward the packet to an address in PC1\u0026#39;s subnet, specifically R1\u0026#39;s G0/1 IP address.\n\nOther pings can test PC1\u0026#39;s default gateway setting, but a ping of PC2 from router R1 cannot.",
        "difficulty":  "2",
        "comments":  "\u003cp\u003e\n\t4/16 -ok as-is,\u0026nbsp; \u0026quot;Two routes are not verified by the Ping used in this question. The Ping originates from R1, and because R1 sends the ping packet out its g0/2 interface. R1 uses that interface\u0026rsquo;s IP address as the source IP address. As a result, the routes used in succession are:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\n\t1) R1\u0026rsquo;s route to PC2\u0026rsquo;s subnet\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\n\t2) R2\u0026rsquo;s route to PC2\u0026rsquo;s subnet\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\n\t3) PC2\u0026rsquo;s default gateway\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\n\t4) R2\u0026rsquo;s route to the R1-R2 subnet\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\n\tFrom that perspective, you can see that the two correct answers are indeed correct.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\n\tThe use of the Extended Ping command as discussed in Ch 18 of the CCNA Cert Guide Vol 1 would allow the Engineer to specify the source address or source port of the Ping.\u0026nbsp; Setting the source address to 192.168.1.1 would confirm R2 having a route to that subnet.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n",
