        "explanation":  "The show ip interfaces command output from IOS XE lists four lines about enabled interface ACLs. If the configuration uses the ip access-group common\u0026hellip; out command, it defines two ACLs in the same direction: A common ACL and a regular ACL. The show ip interface command output lists those two ACLs on separate consecutive lines. Alternately, suppose the configuration uses the ip access-group\u0026hellip; out interface subcommand, which omits the common keyword. In that case, it defines a normal ACL for that direction \u0026ndash; and informs the router not to use a common ACL.\n\nIf no ip access-group command exists under the interface for a given direction, both output lines list \u0026ldquo;not set\u0026rdquo; at the end of the output lines.\n\nIn this question, the output lists ACL names on all four lines, revealing that the configuration commands for both directions use the common keyword. Focusing on the two lines which begin \u0026ldquo;Outgoing,\u0026rdquo; the output does not state \u0026ldquo;not set\u0026rdquo; but lists words \u0026ldquo;one\u0026rdquo; and \u0026ldquo;two.\u0026rdquo; You can infer that \u0026ldquo;one\u0026rdquo; and \u0026ldquo;two\u0026rdquo; are ACL names. You can infer that the configuration includes the ip access-group common one two out command, referring to the ACLs named one and two. \n\nSimilarly, the two output lines beginning \u0026ldquo;Incoming\u0026rdquo; lists two names rather than the text \u0026ldquo;not set,\u0026rdquo; so you can infer the use of the ip access-group common \u0026hellip; in interface subcommand. As shown, the configuration must include the ip access-group common three four in command.",
